\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \li0\ri0\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin0\itap0\pararsid1315844 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Track 1}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Jamaica: family and early life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Born 1932, Jamaica. Lived there until 1951. Born into coloured middle class Jamaican family, the elite, saw themselves as future governing class.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Paternal grandfather kept drugstore. Father worked all early working life with United Fruit Co, ending up as Chief Accountant, first Jamaican to do so. Father\rquote 
s family lived in Old Harbour.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Mother\rquote s family very different. Maternal grandmother a postmistress; grandfather \lquote Jamaica white\rquote , Grosset, much fairer. Mother\rquote 
s family in Port Antonio, prominent. Then a prosperous banana port. Her uncles the leading doctor and lawyer, informally adopted her. Ancestor John Grosset was plantation 
owner and anti-abolition MP. Family owned nearby small estate, Norwich, where mother brought up with cousins. She adored and idealised uncle and aunt, imbibed habits of a plantation girl.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Married 1918. Handsome, strong, self-willed. The family her work. Always felt had settled for a slightly lower standard of living.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Brother George 12 years older, had pigmentosa, went blind, couldn\rquote 
t work, bright and  sweet, loved by family. Sister Pat 6 years older, had turbulent adolescence. Stuart the last child; much da
rker, always felt he was an anomaly. Never felt at home kin family who identified with English rather than with local Jamaicans. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Father quiet, studious, never stopped mother from doing anything.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Remembers 1938 riots. Family in panic. But Stuart had alread
y heard popular attitudes from kitchen talk with servants. Already knew how society graded. Grandmother could pinpoint people\rquote s ancestry. At their Sunday rum punch parties the talk was about affairs, and class  distinctions mediated through colour.
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Later c
ame to see Jamaica as one of the most complex social structures anywhere, a diaspora layered by different migrations: Lebanese and Syrian traders, Indian indentured labourers, Chinese, etc. But no formal racial divisions. Had to be read and managed inform
ally. Because a colony, the ideal social norm was external. Everything lopsided, but a rich social matrix.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Linking of class and race. Class from owning land, buying education. But also graded by colour: the black mass, brown middle class, elite who could pa
ss as white. Had been substantial miscegenation, so many black families had a distant white ancestor. No indigenous population. Intricate elaboration of distinctions. Everybody knew the system, but how related to slavery was taboo, talked about with euphe
misms. Many of his later preoccupations came from this early experience. People did not understand race, but used colour as a signifying system. As a child in Jamaica, learned how to read a society.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Did not know mother\rquote s family well, saw little of them. Snooty that she had married a Jamaican. Strongest family influence from mother: \lquote she  governed our lives
\rquote . Had four servants in uniform, plus gardener. When independence coming, she said, \lquote our way of life is finished\rquote .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Father\rquote s family in Old Harbour, small pr
ovincial fishing town. Ten aunts living in one small house; one aunt ran a school in the yard. Grandmother wonderful, humorous. Christmas contrast: formality at home, but Old Harbour house teaming with people, relatives, friends clergy, gossips and jokes.
 Authentic feel. Adored grandmother, wears her wedding ring. Poles apart from mother\rquote s austere home with tennis court and false atmosphere.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 When father took him to Kingston Cricket Club, felt others were poking fun at him. Stuart knew all about black famili
es too, their complicated relationship with the land, b ut was not one of them. Could not talk to father.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 For mother, Stuart was \lquote the bad one\rquote , naughty, rude. She was  the disciplinarian. But she had a feeling for him as a rebel, strong spirit. Never felt lov
ed by her. Never found a modus vivendi with parents. Mother would never allow him to bring a black boy from Jamaica College home, would learn bad habits from him, we don\rquote t know his parents.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Children brought up in hothouse way. Doesn\rquote t remember brother b
ringing a girlfriend or sister a boyfriend home. But Stuart went out cycling, to parties, met girls. Sister went to work, fell in love with a black medical student at UW
I: mother forbad it. They broke it off: sister had mental breakdown. Stuart saw whole m
icrocosm of Jamaican society and its problems mirrored inside the family culture: she was sacrificed to it. Stuart sees emotional and social as always linked. Saw sister\rquote s fate as emotional death. Wanted to leave and to study elsewhere.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 So mother a governing force
. Pleased by Stuart winning a Rhodes Scholarship to Oxford; brought him there, and later visited him. Heard Stuart speaking at CND rally in Trafalgar Square. She told him not to come home, he wouldn\rquote t fit in in Jamaica.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Schools in Jamaica}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 At schools, always did well. Started at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 prep school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  run by sister of Una Marson, very religious.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Scholarship as dayboy to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Jamaica College [1944-51]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 . Elite secondary school, modelled on English public schools, with tuck shop and ivy-covered chapel. All Caribbean lea
ders went to one of these schools. Michael Manley at school with Stuart. Exams marked in England. History was about England, without history of Empire or slavery> Wordsworth\rquote 
s landscapes. By then pupils mixed, including black boys, country boys, Jews, Syri
ans, children of ex-pats. Many ex-pat as well as Jamaican teachers. History teacher Scots who married a white Jamaican. When a Jamaican, Chambers, finally became head master, some Jamaican history introduced.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Always close to top of class. Played cricket, football, good at tennis \endash  due to learning on mother\rquote 
s court, although she never invited him to play with her fiends. Started to explore Kingston by bicycle. Living in two worlds.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Intellectual influence of history teacher. Encouraged Stuart to read }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Keesings  Archives}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  for contemporary history. Big eye-opener. Found pamphlets attacking Communism, so then tried reading Lenin on imperialism.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Became head boy. Took A levels twice, staying on to get Jamaica scholarship: one of five best students in country.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Sources of re-education}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
That year taught in small country school in Spalding, also a revelation. Run by progressive educationist. Experience of meeting bright country boys and their families. Decided to become a teacher.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Other sources of re-education. Institute of Jamaica library had a children\rquote 
s section: books on Italian art, poetry, etc. Read voraciously. Discovered T. S. Eliot, poems on depressed people, references to Freud. Wanted to know more.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Through school friend  discovered modern jazz, Charlie Parker, Miles Davis. 
Loves Jamaican music, dances to it, but this was another kind of black music. Asks, what is the Harlem Renaissance?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Political context: identified with growing mood for independence, like many others at school. In parallel, cultural revival. Edna Manley\rquote 
s circle of artists and poets. Albert Huie. New interest in indigenous sources. New theatre. All led by nationalists and modernists.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Importance of living in Kingston, colonial metropolis, full of life and diversity. But unable to hook creatively int
o it. Never wanted to be English but needed to explore a wider world. Wanted to leave, in order to connect and return. His life a pattern of zigzags round road blocks.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Classic Jamaican music at this time was folksong and mento. Ska and reggae came with in dependence.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 [Break]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Even at that time could not cycle everywhere in Kingston. Nevertheless through friends met lower class families. His family home near Half Way Tree in Upper Kingston; they went down to the centre by harbour to shop. Rastafarian group near railway station.
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Family servants left late evening to return to flats in tenement yards, returning to serve family breakfast. Gardener involved in ecstatic church. Spent more time with cook than mother, would listen to servants talking in back yard.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Evangelical church next to grandmother\rquote s house, African rhythm of music. Friend in Jamaican dance company. Stuart spoke patois \endash 
 outside home and school. Mother understood but would not speak it. She could sing folksongs. Fluidity of distinctions.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Aware of black consciousness movement, Garveyites, recovery of history of slavery. Never called people \lquote black\rquote , called them \lquote coloured\rquote 
. Stuart became aware of blackness through the Civil Rights Movement. In England, became black and West Indian The West Indian novel created in London. \lquote I am a diasporic subject\rquote .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 

\par 
\par 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 9 April 2012}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Track 2}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Coming to England}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Came to England 1951, by ship to Bristol, with mother, and a huge trunk. First impression, England seemed both familiar, as the countryside, and strange, as dark wet sum
mer August weather. Two months in London as tourists: visited Festival of Britain, Houses of Parliament, saw \lquote The Mousetrap\rquote . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Stayed at International House in Bayswater. Saw a stream of Jamaicans coming out of Paddington, start of post-Windrush migration, like him escaping Jamaica where didn\rquote 
t fit, but not like himself. Mainly country people, unskilled, with felt hats, bright dresses and baskets. They came to work. \lquote Here was my problem on the station platform\rquote : thinking, what will happen to them, will they
 get work, how will they change? Like himself, they would be transformed, and never really able to go home. Through this, learnt to see life as diasporic, in time, in space, always thinking of somewhere else; \lquote a critical experience for me\rquote 
, for the first time saw himself from outside. Published }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Young Englanders}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  later [1969]
, but this has been a lifelong theme.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Oxford}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Merton College, Oxford}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
, to read English Literature [1951-54]. Had not met English upper classes before, seemed very strange. But also retu
rning servicemen, more serious, and working class scholarship boys. Some Indian but no black students in college. Tried to become a literary scholar, involved in debates about literary theory, F. R. Leavis. Learnt a lot from American Rhodes Scholars. Eage
rly reading }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Scrutiny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Tutor Hugo V. Dyson-Dyson a \lquote magnificent anachronism\rquote , learned, urbane, tutorials followed by sherry: then to visit retired scholar Garrard or go to the pub. 
\lquote My taste of urbane life\rquote . All essays for him, but little comment.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 But was influenced by external tutors. Helen Gardner, T. S. Eliot scholar, very impressive. Taught metaphysical poetry. Ovid\rquote 
s sexual puns in Latin. Also Edna Bednarovski, taught Chaucer. Also heard lectures by Lord David Cecil, G. D. H. Cole. Clubs. But no particular staff influence. Dyson thought Stuart was a future Governor? But students were bright, did learn from them.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Key influence from group of Trinidadians, young civil servants being trained for independence to work with Eric Williams, learning development ec
onomics. Although older, his natural cohort: \lquote that is where I became West Indian\rquote . Much talk about Jamaican politics, independence, anti-colonial movements. Met West Indian writers, novelists: Naipaul, Lamming, Selvon, Brathwaite,
 all in England. Stuart had come as a Jamaican, but now West Indian politics, life and literature became major concerns. Discovered Caribbean literature and identity created outside the region.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Oxford Left }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Third major reference group the Oxford Left. Contact from early on. Went on anti-nuclear bomb demonstration with Chuck Taylor and Raphael Samuel,
 who organised it, 1952, well before CND. Most of group were Communist Party members, but Stuart and his friend Alan Hall never joined, although certainly intrigued by Marx. Also Bro
ad Labour Left, and Third World anti-colonialists. Almost all students and post-graduates.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Raphael Samuel, Peter Sedgwick, Gabriel Pearson, Stanley Mitchell \endash  small group at Balliol, all very clever, mostly under the wing of Christopher Hill. As CP members
 banned from Labour Party meetings, but could go to Labour Club open meetings. Cold War suspicion of them. Mingling became easier after 1956. Stuart went to Labour Club, but joined neither party. Didn\rquote t accept Soviet Union as \lquote paradigm case
\rquote . Lecture by ascetic Communist Palme Dutt: thought, he would have been sent to Siberia! But after 1956 did go to CP meetings, started to debate with them and criticise heir \lquote antediluvian\rquote  concepts of class.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Raphael \lquote an extraordinary person\rquote , from a CP family, \lquote a luminary
, very clever, full of ideas, learned about left history. Stuart previously only knew British history of maritime battles, now learnt more social and political history. Gabriel a literary scholar, magnificent raconteur, Dickens, Henry James. Not a practic
a
l revolutionary. Stanley Mitchell read Russian, so had a different connection to Soviet experience. Fine translation of Pushkin. David Marquand from Labour. Others hoping for future political careers, like Brian Walden. Among Conservatives then in Oxford,
 Michael Heseltine. Tariq Ali became President of Oxford Union.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Starting research}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Went on to Ph D, supported by Jamaica Scholarship. Wanted to write on American novels in 1930s, but told too recent. Eventually chose Henry James \endash 
 aristocratic, uninterested in black people, but had an international consciousness, a diasporic novelist writing about Americans in Europe. Never finished.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Began reading about anthropology and culture in Rhodes House Library. Debate on African retentions under slavery. Patois a ling
uistic fusion. Why are Caribbeans not at home in any one culture? Read Edith Clarke on Jamaican family, Henriques on sexuality, Elsa Goveia on history.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Had lost confidence in becoming a writer, not succeeding with poetry or novels. Wrote for \lquote Caribbean Voices\rquote 
 on BBC World Service. Feels his training in criticism destroyed his capacity for creative writing. Decided to become a reviewer and critic. Published some pieces in Caribbean journals, but first important article was for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  (Note 1)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
