\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Universities and Left Review}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ) came out of Left debates in Oxford between CP and Labour and Third World Groups. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 was intended to connect them. Raphael revived former Socialist Club (which still 
had income from earlier members) which became centrepiece. 1956 traumatic: most CP members left the Party. So now a much larger independent Left.  Raphael suggested starting a journal. Older CP group, led by E. P. Thompson and John Saville, had also left 
Party; Raphael invited them to contribute.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Meanwhile widespread big debate on the future of working class culture. Would it follow the American model, mass culture, TV? Was capitalism changing? Or class? From start }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  opposed simple base-superstructure mod
el, gave culture and literature a real influence. This was to be a future key thread in cultural studies. In 1959 General Election Gaitskell was asking whether affluence would undo working class consciousness. Debate about capitalism also cultural. This f
ocus gave special quality to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 as a forum. One of Stuart\rquote 
s earliest articles in on this theme, in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Out of Apathy.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  Wrote an early piece for }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 New Left Review}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , editors refused his title, \lquote A sense of classlessness\rquote . (Note 2) 
Other contemporary work includes }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Affluent Worker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , and Raphael on New Towns.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 was launched on basis of Raphael\rquote 
s belief it would be well subscribed. The group by then breaking up, Chuck returning to Canada, Gabriel leaving. Given credit by printers of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Tribune}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 . First number sold very fast, Raphael ordered another 3,000. Financial help from Chuck Taylor.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Partisan Coffee House launched after 1957. But they had formed a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 readers\rquote  club in London, hiring halls. Raphael chose decor. For first meeting, 750 came to hear Isaac Deutscher. He had written for first }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , they went to Reading to persuade him; then he was furious when Raphael added a footnote to the article
. Eventually regular meetings at 100 Oxford St jazz club. Brought in people from CP historians group; also from Free Cinema, 
Karel Reisz, making films on working class; and drama, Arnold Wesker. Speakers included Richard Crossman, Tony Crosland, Hugh Gaitskell, Tom Mboya. Debates on NATO, the bomb. Became huge centre of discussion.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Partisan became long-term home in Soho Squa
re. Coffee and chess in basement. No room for big meetings, which continued elsewhere. Crucial Oxford meeting at All Souls voted against Raphael\rquote 
s proposal for a French-style coffee bar, but he went ahead. Raphael bought beetroot for borscht himself. Opposite the Partisan was the Gaggia bar, first Italian espresso machine in London \endash  a rival model for the future.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Offices upstairs and a room for small meetings \endash  groups on education and schools, films, met there. Leafleting for first Aldermaston march organis
ed from there. Setting up black-white tenants\rquote  groups after 1958 Notting Hill riots. Tough period, racism surfaced and connected with new Teddy Boy culture. Got to know Michael X, Michael de Freitas,
 Notting Hill street boss, controlled prostitutes and evicted tenants for Rachman \endash  but he somehow wanted to change, and gave them contacts. So the club became more of an activist centre.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Fusion between }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ULR}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
 and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 New Reasoner}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
 [of ex-CP historians]. Always felt close; then developed joint editorial meetings, and cross-representation. Financially difficult to keep both afloat, so decided to pool resources in one journal, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 New Left Review}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  (}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 NLR}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ). Edward and Dorothy Thompson worn out by effort of journalism, Yorkshire peace movement, etc: visiting them in Halifax. Big la
unch. Pooled  editorial Board, so now included John Rex, Peter Worsley, Alistair Macintyre, Raymond Williams, Doris Lessing. Stuart chosen as editor, but felt he didn\rquote 
t know enough about British politics, a neophyte among titans. Editorial meetings became a nightmare as \lquote the fathers\rquote 
 denounced his plans. John Saville, chairman, gave some protection against the wrath of the Thompsons, who were sticklers for editorial procedures, and deeply suspicious of Londoners. Went to Halifax for meetings, Hull to confer with Saville.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
At same time also working for CND, usually did a meeting at least once a  fortnight, rushing around England: speaking to trade unions, labour clubs, pacifists. His first practical political experience.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Edward P. Thompson very powerful, imaginative, romantic, fine social historian. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
The Making of the English Working Class}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  \endash  which Stuart read in manuscript \endash  opened a whole new field of history. Would go with Catherine to their cottage at Vodi
 in Wales; they were very kind, but formidable. Could talk together about William Morris and Blake. But had no sense of what colonialism meant, very English in his imagination. Wrote long letter to Stuart about }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Policing the Crisis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , asking why go on so about race? European historians didn\rquote t see colonialism and
 slavery as a route to capitalism, or know much about it. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Making}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
 did take cultural dimension seriously, including religion. Despite closeness, always a tense relationship. Later got still tenser, Edward hated cultural studies, culminating in History Wo
rkshop debate when he savaged Richard Johnson, one of his devotees: parting of the ways.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Raymond Williams was organising extramural work in the south-east for Oxford, met him through this. Talked to Raymond with Alan Hall. In 1956 Raymond sent early draft 
chapters for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Culture and Society}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
. Huge range of imagination, but while Edward became wilder when excited, hair flying, Raymond went soft and quiet. Very approachable, and because of his literary formation, intellectually closer. He joined }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 NLS}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  editors: mentor, long and wonderful friendship. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
