\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Track 3}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Marriage to Catherine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Met Catherine early 1960s, after Aldermaston march. She was 18, 13 years younger; Stuart already well established in New Left, Catherine about to go as undergradu
ate to Sussex. Met through Mike Rustin, married to Cath\rquote s older sister Margaret. Difficult time because her father, \lquote wonderful man\rquote 
, had suffered severe stroke, paralysed. Her parents then moved to London leaving Cath in Leeds to complete A levels. Also difficult for Stuart, deciding not to return to Jamaica.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Catherine went to Sussex to study History, Stuart to work in Birmingham; he went every weekend to Brighton. But Cath didn\rquote 
t get on with Trotskyist activists. So they married and settled in Birmingham autumn 1964. She read History at Birmingham with Rodney Hilton.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
It took a long time to equalise the balance between them. Stuart writing masculinist love letters, assuming the man led. Eventually both could learn from the other, shift in the balance.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Cath started mediaeval Ph D with Rodney Hilton, but then became pregnant. Stuart teaching flat out. She was ripe for Feminism. With other young mothers, started cr\'e8
che, school, shared caring \endash  feminist neighbourhood network. Difficult period for them as a couple
. He found it hard to develop an alterative approach. Women wanted to hear women, not men. Relationship transformed. He could no longer assume their inequality. Had to accept her friends he didn\rquote 
t like. Had to decide whether they wanted open marriage or monogamy. Cath actively involved in sexual politics. Problems bringing up children: give  boys guns, like he had? Creche set up, \lquote Pumpkin Shell\rquote 
, many of men involved, looking after children while women in discussion groups.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Always aware of being a mixed couple. His relation to Jamaica, his first \lquote home\rquote 
, made him feel different. Fewer mixed couples then. Problem finding a place to live. People shouting abuse, especially at Cath. But not an emotional focus. They went to Jamaica, Cath met his family, and eventu
ally did research there. Visiting rural Baptist chapels.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Stuart was having little to do with his family. After marriage they went home in a banana boat. Mixed couples not then welcome in Jamaica. The two families never met. Cath
\rquote s family from Yorkshire. Her father well-known Liberal Baptist minister, head of college in Oxford. Mother\rquote 
s family millers. Parents met at Oxford. Mother a bluestocking. They accepted Stuart without hesitation. Stuart cut off from his parents because they were interfering with the relationship.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 For a period he didn\rquote t go to Jamaica, transition to staying in England. Then mother and sister visited 1963-4. Stuart always involved in Caribbean politics and writing
. His fellow students at Jamaica College inherited role of colonial elite. Michael Manley later a friend, interviewed him for BBC \lquote Redemption Song\rquote . Closer friends active in PNP \endash 
 teachers, troublesome students. Identified with what was happening, but could take no active role. How to reconnect with all this? Remembers 1938 rioting, rumours of mobs, and mother: \lquote This is the end of our world\rquote .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 School and adult education teaching }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Stuart dropped Ph D, became Secondary School supply teacher. Living in Clapham, with Haston family: she was political refugee from South Africa, both mili
tant Trotskyists, became a family for him. Job at Kennington Secondary Modern, within a month a class teacher. Every evening to Soho to edit ULR, sometimes to 2 am: double life. His class 4 Remove, all had failed 11+. Tried to teach them English grammar. 
They were rowdy, rude, threatening, and lovable. Teaching English, tried \lquote Romeo and Juliet, reading stories. Keeping kids off the street.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Wrote about them in ULR article, \lquote Absolute beginners\rquote , on birth of youth culture and racism. (Note 3)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Boys from his class went to Notting Hill 1958, told him there was \lquote trouble with the blackies\rquote , playing loud music and 
\lquote taking our women: shouted abuse at black people, egged on by their fathers. After riots New Left started work there. School had minority black population.
 Black settlement just beginning, no active black politics yet. Brixton had older settled black population, Notting Hill more transient, multi-occupied flats.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 At same time teaching Adult Education for Raymond Williams, based in Oxford. Stuart became staff 
tutor in Kent, teaching classes on novels weekly in Bexley Heath. Exciting, intensely political class. Ben Brewster\rquote s family; later translator of Althusser. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Also teaching at British Film Institute. Met Paddy Whannel, working class, in charge of education 
at BFI: preparing extracts for teaching film in schools. Stuart lecturing on film appreciation in universities etc. Then hired at Chelsea College of Science and Technology then Chelsea Polytechnic] 
to teach film and media. Became involved in movement in English teaching profession to include media. Wrote }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Popular Arts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  [1964\} with Whannel to support this. Book is a teaching manual with projects.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 This was a turning point: becoming a critic had undermined his creative potential as novelist or poet. \lquote Caribbean Voices\rquote 
 programmes on BBC World Service, meeting Caribbean novelists. Like them, he became West Indian in London. Saw his role as helping people to understand popular culture as a critic: influenced by the social seriousness of Leavis rather than Oxford
 dilletantism, but did not accept Leavis\rquote  sense of cultural decline.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Stuart had always been interested in popular element of culture, but it became intellectually more central. Had gone to cinema weekly with an aunt, saw musicals, westerns, every Humphrey Bogart film. Film the most exciting 20}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\super\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 th}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
 C art form. Also interested in Jamaican popular culture. Began to see that different criteria were applied to high and popular culture: social judgements behind this. Chandler\rquote s use of language as good as Steinbeck\rquote s. Evaluating through 
\lquote the direct response\rquote  was like Leavis\rquote s \lquote lived experience. Feeling Carlyle is \lquote a racist pig\rquote 
. Tolstoy opens up a more subtle understanding of relationships, Chandler less deep. Should discriminate between particular works rather than categories. This all leads towards cultural studies.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Birmingham and Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies [1964-79]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Went to Birmingham 1964, after marrying Catherine. Had been much interest in Oxford Socialist Club in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Uses of Literacy}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 ; and more gene
rally, in how mass culture relates to mass consciousness. How do ordinary people perceive contradiction? They hate complex moral judgements of philosophers. Ideas of fate. Indirect ways of reading popular culture as evidence. Why did people respond? Were 
they simply being manipulated? They bring some of their own experience to watching TV, like \lquote East Enders\rquote , in response to these apparently corrupt sources. He wrote a piece on this, \lquote Deconstructing popular culture\rquote 
, opposing both the folk culture tradition, and the idea of manipulation: truth is in between. (Note 4)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 So need an interpretative methodology. Cultural studies reads films partly in context of deeper social causes and effects.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Came to Birmingham because Hoggart knew his work, and Stuart had staged 
a discussion between Hoggart and Williams. Invited Stuart to come as a Research Fellow and set up group to work on popular arts. As the first staff member, planned the Centre with Hoggart, chose the name, Centre for Contemporary Cultural Studies: a rallyi
ng point, seeking to attract graduate students from literature, history etc. Raymond\rquote s crucial insight that not just high culture, culture as a way of life, as anthropology. Terrain defined by work of Hoggart and Williams.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Popular culture also a political issue. Would Labour survive affluence and mass culture, TVs, etc. Debates with Crosland and Gaitskell. Mark Abrams on the }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Sun}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , \lquote demotic populism.\rquote 
 Hoggart understood the political relevance of cultural debate. Mass advertising, Elvis Presley \endash  what did it tell you?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Hoggart good to work with, kind, generous, soft-spoken: tough-minded but unassertive. Recently married, his wife supportive. Did not think in political categories. Inherited Leavisite suspicion of theory. But he accepted need to know more of socia
l side, as Stuart did of imaginative side: a successful partnership \endash  until later. Interdisciplinary bunch of students.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Richard taught how to read culture through texts \endash  D. H. Lawrence, Orwell; Stuart taught theory, from sociology, and from Marxism. Lidia Curti
 came from Italy, introduced them to Gramsci. They were all \lquote making up\rquote  cultural studies: too early to teach in an academic style, there was no accepted body of knowledge and research. So from the start, working in a co
-operative way. Levi-Strauss. By 1968, Marx and Freud reading groups.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Began to institutionalise discussion groups as working groups: on media, on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Making}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , women on Juliet Mitchell. Some groups developed their own projects, diverting students from their Ph Ds, but resulting in the ear
ly books. Collective practice spreading through the Centre.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 CCCS and social theory}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 By third wave of students, Stuart began teaching theory. Translation of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Prison Notebooks}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  \lquote became my Bible\rquote ; \lquote if I am anything I am a Gramscian\rquote . Always a revisionist. Similarly, read much on Freud, but not a Freudian or Kleinian. Inte
rest in European social theory: read Weber, Durkheim, Marx, Simmel, Schutze. All contributed to new field of cultural studies. Publication of early Marx. Humanist Marx opened pathway between Marx
ism and culture. Never saw culture as simply dependent, as in classical Marxism. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Onslaught from 1950s of American sociology: Talcott Parsons, Merton. British empirical traditions. Later influence of deviancy and interactionism. With Parsons, culture is in
ert, produces no meanings. The \lquote cultural turn\rquote  in studies, privileging of culture. Germs of cultural theory in Hoggart, Williams, Edward Thompson. Debate on cultural foundations of politics. Cultural historians appear.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Then struck asunder by arrival of European socio-linguistic theory: Roland Barthes, Levi-Strauss \endash  \lquote the linguistic turn\rquote 
. Language as a system in which meaning is constituted. Rediscovery of Saussure. Meaning is constructed through difference. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Educare}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 : education, educator, educated. Stuart st
ill believed in total explanations through a modified Marxism. Power of language to persuaded, convert. Questions of power and meaning central for Foucault, second wave of influence of French theory, rise of \lquote cultural theory\rquote 
. Stuart saw this more as a form of social theory. Culture is not autonomous, but there is always a dimension of signification: Baudelaire, \lquote Everything that exists is also a sign\rquote . Weber in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Methodology of the Social Sciences}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  on how you interpret seeing a tree cut down \endash  you mobilise the meanings in your culture.
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The use of \lquote codes\rquote 
 comes from structural linguistics. Saussure oh how we interpret a light changing from green to red. Codes are basic to culture, often outside our awareness, but we use them to think with. En-coding and de-coding pamphlet.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 30 April 2012}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Track 4}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Stuart thought of becoming a psychoanalyst because of sister\rquote 
s mental breakdown. Not allowed to marry a black man. He started to read Freud. But realised would need a medical training, so gave it up.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Influence of inter
actionism: an alternative to mainstream positivist sociology with a more interpersonal level of analysis. Close ethnographic work found in deviancy studies. Mainstream focussed on the maintenance of order; but Ch
icago school on studies of gangs, underworld, migrants, crime. Howard Becker. Interactionism provided background for CCCS youth studies and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Resistance to Rituals}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  [1976]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Labelling theory a development from this: response of control culture to deviance. Critical criminology: work of Stan Cohen, labelling by press and state. How does society react to young people\rquote s behaviour? Stan\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Folk Devils and Moral Panics}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  a critical influence.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 General social crisis in mid-1970s \endash  students, trade unions rebel; Heath says Britain is \lquote ungovernable\rquote  \endash  a conjuncture. Saw street crime as a 
\lquote moral panic\rquote . No real figures: a wider fear of change \endash  affluence, black youth. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Mugging }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 as a title symbolised this social crisis. [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Policing the Crisis: Mugging, the State and Law and Order}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , 1978] Would we follow America: press headline, \lquote Harlem comes to Handsworth\rquote . General ethos of fear.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Phil Cohen gave work on youth culture more of a class dimension. Himself political, deviant, East Ender, understood background. Different fractions of working class youth, traditional and modern. But many sociologists saw studying this as \lquote 
just froth\rquote . }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 John Rex not a theoretical influence, although as a Weberian had an interesting approach. More important in mapping how race played out in Birmingham.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Every social practice is also social. At start looked for a theory in sociology. Read Parsons, Merton, but also the masters, Weber and Durkheim. Durkheim\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Ann\'e9e Sociologique}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  period and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Elementary Forms of the Religious Life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  much more relevant that his more statistical }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Suicide. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Similarly Weber had a  caus
al pathway and a historical pathway. Although not trained in sociology, they were drawing on a wide range of sociological thinking.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 CCCS method }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Was there a distinctive CCCS method? Brian Roberts emphasised participant observation, but they did not do much
 of this, or of individual interviewing. Originally many others thought they were in media studies, but not interested in this approach, wanted to be more critical and social.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Encoding and decoding paper was a critique of American mass communication studies. Then only two centres in Britain, CCCS and Halloran\rquote s at Leicester.
 Encoding and decoding given as paper to international conference in Leicester. Simplistic \lquote hypodermic model\rquote : the media cause people to act deviantly. Not enough: you must deal with mea
ning. Media reports of events are stories, part of the sphere of language: the influence comes through a narrative discursive form, not as simple reality.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 At the other end of the causal chain, people may decode with different meanings. Need to share linguistic codes. Barthes
s on advertising, the story that can be imagined from a photo. No simple influence of media. Content analysis alone not enough.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 How do you analyse a TV programme? Like literary analysis: of aesthetic forms, language, wages. After this, n
eed to consider how audience are responding: by looking at social scene. They should have done group interviews with audience, a weakness that they didn\rquote t. Difficult because processes partly unconscious \endash 
 like the use of grammar when speaking. Later on, Dave Morley worked on language in industrial disputes. They were hesitant to interview, because Birmingham Sociology Department said they were not trained to do so.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Groups at CCCS }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Groups at CCCS. Initially no model to follow. Hoggart had applied literary analysis to mass media. Not clear what to read: made it up \endash  Leavis, Saussure,
 Hoggart, Raymond Williams, Edward Thompson. Students mixed, from literature and history. So needed reading groups. Graduate studies in Britain then not well developed, little methods teaching \endash 
 but hence freer to experiment. At start, one group with Hoggart, cultural analysis of literary texts; another group with Stuart, exploring theory. Other groups of students focussing on media, deviancy, literature and language, social history
. Later reading groups on Marx; Freud; Feminism; race; oral history; education.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Series of linked pamphlets, publishing the joint work of groups. Creating a common conversation on cultural studies. Group work on Communist Our History; or on women\rquote 
s magazines. Education group published a book with Richard Johnson; feminist group too; media group published }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Culture Media and Ideology}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 . Theses on youth culture and deviancy led to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Resistance to Rituals}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 . John Clarke, Charles Critcher researching working class culture, sport and entertainment. Tony Jefferson on youth culture. Angela McRobbie on girls\rquote  culture. 
Clarke, Critcher, Jefferson and Brian Roberts (in Sociology, researching Chicago School) worked on }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Policing the Crisis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 . Ad hoc structures.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Charles Critcher lived in Handsworth, very active in local anti-racist work. He alerted them to over-sentencing of young \lquote muggers\rquote 
, given 20 years each. Group then started research on how this connected with wider social anxieties. Many of group were also attending and presen
ting papers at National Deviancy Symposium with Stan Cohen, Joch Young, Laurie Taylor. All the group also teaching and writing theses. All politically aware, going on anti-racist marches. Birmingham very alert to these issues. Powell\rquote 
s speech. Most of group from respectable working class or lower middle class backgrounds; all had been to university.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Women included Angela McRobbie, Rachel Powell. They knew about emerging youth culture, rock music, women\rquote s magazines.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Research for }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Policing the Crisis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  started 1
972, book published 1978. Hey were creating a field of study. Informal, independent. Staff originally Stuart and Richard Hoggart. Then Michael Green joined them from English |Department; then Richard John son appointed (made contact during 1968 sit-in}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 came from History in Commerce Faculty. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Track 5}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 For cultural studies they borrowed theory eclectically. Model of encoding-decoding is drawn from Marx\rquote s }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Grundrisse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 : adding more and more levels of determination. Foucault: concepts are tools to think with. Unlik
e Althusser, did not believe you could only understand a concept in its particular framework. Great theorists themselves not consistent through their working lives. Believed in hermeneutic interpretative method, not positivist, like historians, with no fi
nal proof.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 One group project was on press treatment of 1968 events.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Director of CCCS [1974-79]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Struck by how Cultural Studies has grown since then. Has spread, first to Italy, then to USA, and changed at lot. Not so much a single field as a set of preoccupa
tions. Stuart is opposed to some new developments; much rubbish in both sociology and cultural studies. Key concern is how culture relates to our non-cultural practices. More departments of Cultural Studies outside Britain; here specialists are hidden in 
other departments.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Richard Hoggart was on University Senate; in change of this radical Centre, which took a leading role in 1968 events. So very exposed; other senior staff expected him to control his students. Decided to accept UNESCO offer of job in cultu
ral policy for three to four years. First attempt to close the Centre, saved by protests  from Hoggart and Halloran at Leicester.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Stuart made Acting Director, but not professor; told he was seen as an \lquote outsider, a cuckoo in the nest\rquote . For years later the s
ame crisis when Hoggart decided not to return, another attempt to close Centre, and finally, Stuart Director, 1974-79.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Marx a key point of reference. Inspired by his concepts, but did not accept his determinism: Stuart \lquote a revisionist from the beginning\rquote . G
ramsci important because he emphasised questions of power in relation to culture.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 At Naples, head of Department of English and American Studies, Professor Ferrara, Marxist, very interested by Hoggart and Williams\rquote  work. Sent Lidia Curti
 for a year in Birmi
ngham. She re-introduced Stuart to Gramsci. After her return other visitors came from Naples, and a strand of cultural studies was developed in Italy. Lidia was first new joint friend of Stuart and Catherine, and she married at CCCS graduate, Ian Chambers
.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Larry Grossberg, one of the first American students at CCCS, did Ph D at Annenberg School, and took message to USA. Little early interest in France (or now) or Germany (more after 1968).}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Phases of cultural studies: \lquote linguistic turn\rquote  through influence of Saussure; then \lquote theoretical turn\rquote , less the influence of Adorno and Frank
furt School. Debate between humanistic approach and structuralism \endash  from Levi-Strauss and Barthess to Foucault. Stuart had a foot in both camps. (Note 5)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 As Director, did not have over
all plan for change. For regular planning discussions worked with Michael Green, Richard John son, and also Paul Willis (a senior figure who had published two books). Also weekly general meeting of all staff and students. Very participatory.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Why left? Firs
t, because every year students demanded re-writing of course. No longer wanted to keep changing. Second, had tried to run the Centre collaboratively. Students had open access to duplicator. Not always up to tensions this created. Still felt a duty to teac
h. Special difficulty in relating to feminism. As a man not admitted to women\rquote 
s caucus meetings. Students asking for more feminist reading. Had earlier encouraged feminist at CCCS, but did not like to be told by younger women to take a back seat. Important lesson in difference between theory and practice.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Open University [1979-97]}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
Where to go? Would always be marked by CCCS experience. Some approaches from other universities led nowhere. Then Sociology chair vacancy at Open University. Liked less marked disc
iplinary boundaries. Saw it new challenge to make cultural studies intelligible to ordinary students. Willing to \lquote profess\rquote  sociology for the job.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Took cultural studies issues and people into sociology courses. Interested by distance learning, less academic
ally trained students, older and with experience. Main work was writing courses rather than teaching, making supporting radio and TV programmes. Taught summer schools, but missed contact with students.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Most influential courses he wrote were \lquote Beliefs and Ideologies, \lquote The State and Society\rquote , Modern Societies\rquote . Concept of \lquote modernity\rquote 
: four course-books on this. Several of these courses influential.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Political Work }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 His political work an altogether different strand. Bill Schwarz, York graduate, came to work at CCCS as historian. 
Centre never had its own political position. Kept group politics out. But did link culture with political ideas. Personally active in ant-racist work. Later wrote critiques of Thatcherism in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Marxism Today }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 (had been the Communist Party\rquote s theoretical journal, edited by Martin Jacques) and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 New Socialist. Policing the Crisis}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 
 written between crisis of the welfare state and introduction of welfarism, privatisation and restoration of power of private capital. Predicted (in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Marxism Today }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 article) that because old system was falling apart, a Tory populist could get elected. Not all sociological research so accurately predictive! (Note 6) }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Hard Road to Renewal}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  [1988] is a selection of his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Marxism Today }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 articles. This more overt political line did not come directly from cultural studies. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
