\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 21 May 2012}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Track 6}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Open University}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Less contact with students than at other universities. Met them teaching summer schools. Many significant academic colleagues: in department Ken Thompson, Graham Salaman, Paul d
u
 Gay. With mixed course teams also worked with John Clarke, Mike Fitzgerald (social policy and criminology), Doreen Massie (geography), John Allen (geography), David Hill (politics). Course teams an intense experience, last two/three years, many stages of
 
drafting, planning and making radio and TV programmes, publishing course book. Course manager crucial. Later involve experience of the part-time tutors. Courses last five years, so preparation overlaps with them. Course teams bring very close contact with
 colleagues. Not departments, broader faculty.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Althusser}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Interest in Althusser goes back to Gramsci reading book. Much of Althusser translates Gramsci\rquote s concepts into a structuralist idiom\endash 
 such as conjunctures, hegemonic forms of power, different levels of power, historical blocks: new ways of discussing the political. Cultural studies resists Althusser\rquote s formulation of economic determination in the last instance. But Althusser
\rquote s formulation of over-determination can been seen as a clarification of Gramsci\rquote s ideas of conjunctures.  Althusser\rquote 
s structuralism is more French than Hegelian,  focus on the structuralist Marx. Stuart was also interest by non-Marxist structuralism: Levi-Strauss and Barthess in anthropology, Saussure and semiotics. Language as a mode
l of culture provided a more rigorous form of literary analysis. Stuart\rquote 
s essay on the two strands of cultural studies, humanistic and structural: the Centre took the latter path, but the French way rather than the Hegelian path to the Frankfurt school. Al
thusser took structuralism to the extreme, the elements became disconnected, theory cut off from practice.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Modernity}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Modernity then a concept very much in the atmosphere, less so now. Modern means the modern age, modern thought from c 1900. After this the 
developed world developed significantly differently. Stuart thinks historically, respects tradition. But as a boy he felt he could be part of modern life, wanted to know about modern writers and painters, hence wish to study abroad. Similarly West Indian 
n
ovelists came to London. Refused to be shut out of future history because of what happened in the past. What is the impact of American economic dominance, or eclipse of high bourgeois by popular culture, or new issues around feminism and race? Modernity s
i
mply a phrase for summing up these big distinctions from roughly 1880s. First phase of capitalism extracting maximum surplus value gives way to encouraging consumption. Continues beyond First World War. Rise of mass culture, mass politics, mass production
.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Visual Arts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Is interested in photography, but above all in the image: how the image overtakes the written and spoken word as a key carrier of ideas: through TV, photography, advertising
, cinema. Also interested in work of black diaspora artists, who often started with photography. Had always been at the margins, now putting yourself in the frame. Design of shops and malls.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Debate on representation. Critics argue against mimetic approach (imitation of nature). Stuart sees representation as another transform
ation, another level of reality rather than a copy of the real. Visual culture becomes more important with modernity: the camera is a machine which reproduces the world. Conceptions of class come partly from people observing. Not a student of visual arts,
 and does not take photographs, but part of his own intellectual awakening was to see Picasso and other modern painters. Became especially interested in film as medium of modernity.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 His later focus has been on diasporic black artists: second generation, wit
h a double consciousness between Jamaica and London. A few got to art school, and used photography as a form of protest: Eddie Chambers. Comparable to art of black power. Huge creative explosion of such work in 1980s. But galleries not interested, no arts
 schools teach their work. Just little exhibitions in Brixton back streets.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Hence became involved with two organisations inspired by this work: Institute for International Visual Arts 
(INVA) and Association of Black Photographers. From 1980s black filmmakers (Isaac Julian, John Akomfrah
, Steve MacQueen) had similar problems of funding and where to show work. Film workshops. Worked especially with young phographer David Bailey who organised early exhibitions. Became chair of boards of both organisations, whic
h by then were receiving ongoing Arts Council funding. Jointly applied for capital to build a new centre, nearly \'a37 million. Raised half as matching funding. Chairs of INA (Jilane Tawadras, Egyptian) and Black Photographers (Mark
 Healey, from Newcastle) with Stuart raised \'a3one and a half mission from Barclays Bank. Took seven years to build Rivington Place. Young architect, David Adjaye, now well-known.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The focus of Rivington Place is how black people are represented: black and Asian. Holds exhibitions, b u
t not a collection. Current debates on relation nof black art to abstraction and to feminism. No commitment to naturalism: follow the lead of the artists. But black arts do tend to be more figurative.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Describes some of own pictures; man in a urinal. Great abstractionist, Frank Bowling. Stuart has just written on Dennis Morris, Hackney photographer in 1970s
: a striking social documentary, but he also did creative designs for covers of Bob Marley records.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Different }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 [2001] is partly is partly about black ident
ity and the complexity of identity and blackness. Photo by Dennis Morris of a boy in waste ground, clearly going places, not wanting pity; but given caption, \lquote Brother, can you spare a dime?\rquote 
 Or a couple living in a single room, 1960s, squalid, yet the man elegantly dressed with pork pie hat, not to be deterred. Hidden forces of change, resilience. Blackness an emergent, changing category. Focus on routes rather than roots.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Pictures of Everyday Life}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  [1987] from a Commonwealth photographic competition exhibit
ion. Stuart a judge, co-edited the book. Again multiple ways of being marginalised. Qualities of blackness not fixed: slaves, free blacks, etc. Each representation is an active transformation. What matters is the differences.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Impact of post-structuralism}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\ul\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Impact of post-structuralism. Questions any essentialism. Ends and beginnings are just resting points, history never stopes. Derrida criticises binaries:
 differences are a spectrum, and what matters is the passage from one point to another. Marx and language.Stuart\rquote s reorientation from total explanation to acceptance of difference. Difference can be explosive: race, sex. His key essay on this is 
\lquote A reading of Marx\rquote s 1858 preface to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Grundrisse}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 \rquote  (Note 7)
. After that begins to be influenced by Foucault, Benjamin, Bahktin, Levi-Strauss, Barthes
s, Derrida; although not wishing to be a scholar of any of them. Half of Derrida does no understand, and a lot probably nonsense, but does have key ideas on difference.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Stuart has a magpie mind, willing to use ideas for his own issues. For example, recent essay on multiculturalism [}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Multicultural Question}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 , 2001]. Works on interface between concepts and the concrete. Marx on how to produce \lquote 
the concrete in thought\rquote . Doesn\rquote t aspire to be a pure theorist. Very long interest in Marx. Briefer with Sartre, and mainly for his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Question of Method}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  with attack on \lquote lazy Marxism\rquote  in discussing French poetry. We should aim to produce new knowledge, rather than reassure with old insights and formulae.}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
