\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 In te
rms of method, Stuart not against measuring. But figures are not hard evidence as many believe. We need to understand why people believe what they do, how they came to that belief. Figures are just the beginning. Why do beliefs spread, why do they become 
public issues? Favours both surveys and ethnography. Durkheim on facts as \lquote things\rquote ; his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 Suicide}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  we critiqued by James Douglas in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844 The Social Meanings of Suicide.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f39\fs22\insrsid1315844\charrsid1315844  Social facts are things and meanings and practices.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f39\fs22\insrsid1315844 
